      "solution": "numbertext = input()\n\nnumberlist = numbertext.replace('x','0').replace(',','').split('.')\nvalue = float(numberlist[0]+'.'+''.join(numberlist[1:])) / 2\nvaluestring = str(value).strip('0')\n\ndecimal_position = valuestring.find('.')\nbefore = valuestring[:decimal_position]\nafter = valuestring[decimal_position+1:]\nfilled_number = 'x' * (9 - len(before)) + before + after + 'x' * (6 - len(after))\n\nmarkers = [',',',','.','.','']\n\nnumberstring_out = ''\nfor i,marker in zip(range(0,len(filled_number),3),markers):\n    numberstring_out += filled_number[i:i+3] + marker\n\nprint(numberstring_out)",
      "statement": "Based on the specially formatted number [[numberstring]], you need to output the number divided by two in that same special format.\n\nThe <<special format rules>>: a number is always represented as a {{string}} with length {{19}}, which represents a float with 9 numbers before and 6 numbers after the decimal point. All numbers before the decimal point are comma-separated for every three digits, while all numbers after the decimal point are point-separated for every three digits. All positions not used are represented with {{x}}.\n\n<<For example>>: the input {{xxx,x38,858.321.82x}} is {{38858.32182}}. Divided by two this gives {{19429.16091}}, so the output should be {{xxx,x19,429.160.91x}}.",
